# Content Standards and Formatting

## Research Documents
Research documents should follow the template established in [.research/core_knowledge/criminal_law/homicide/README.md](mdc:.research/core_knowledge/criminal_law/homicide/README.md):

1. Overview section introducing the topic
2. Detailed breakdown of subtopics
3. References to primary and secondary sources
4. Case law citations with proper format
5. Implementation notes and related documents

## Test Materials
Test documents should follow the format in [.tests/criminal_law/homicide_test.md](mdc:.tests/criminal_law/homicide_test.md):

1. YAML-formatted test overview
2. Structured question sections
3. Detailed grading rubrics
4. Reference materials
5. Implementation guidelines

## Document Structure
Every document should include:
```yaml
Required Sections:
  - Title and Overview
  - Main Content Sections
  - Reference Materials
  - Related Documents
  - Implementation Notes

Formatting:
  - Markdown headings for sections
  - YAML blocks for metadata
  - Code blocks for examples
  - Proper citation format
  - Consistent indentation
```

## Citation Standards
```yaml
Case Law:
  Format: "Case Name (Year)"
  Citation: "Volume Reporter Page"
  Example: "People v. Anderson (1968)"
          "Citation: 70 Cal.2d 15"

Books:
  Format: "Title (Author)"
  ISBN: "Required"
  Chapter: "Specific section"
  Example: "Understanding Criminal Law (Dressler)"
          "ISBN: 978-1531007911"
```

## Quality Guidelines
1. All content must include:
   - Clear learning objectives
   - Assessment criteria
   - Implementation guidance
   - Reference materials
   - Related documents

2. Documentation must be:
   - Comprehensive
   - Well-organized
   - Properly referenced
   - Regularly updated
   - Quality assured
